&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Discussion&amp;#160;&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Often many solutions are available to the architect for defining the approach needed to support the business. With the&#xD;
    added clarity provided through the mathematic analysis of the numbers associated with each approach (e.g., volumetrics,&#xD;
    frequency of occurrence, and other numbers) the best solution and most cost-effective solution often turns out to be&#xD;
    quite obvious. The approach will also likely not run into volume, scaling, or other issues when implemented. Also,&#xD;
    Architecture Decisions to improve the existing business process through advances in automation must be supported by the&#xD;
    analysis of costs and benefits to ensure that they are indeed worthwhile. All too often there is a desire to automate&#xD;
    for the sake of automating without understanding the business benefit or need. A good understanding of the volumes of&#xD;
    data is necessary. Creativity and a very good understanding of the business processes are required to address low&#xD;
    volume service requests in a cost-effective manner.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Some practical suggestions:&amp;#160;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Document volumetrics and keep them current;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Continually monitor capacity to handle current and projected volumes;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Produce regular reports from the system to monitor present volumes, arrival patterns and peak load;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Ensure system capacity can handle peak loads;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Ensure staffing can handle demand volume and peak load within service level agreements.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></mainDescription>
